ce:section.ce:para:
PTs-CDs exhibit a substantially increased killing effect on cancer cells, likely due to their smaller spherical morphology and particle size. Small molecule uptake is facilitated by their small size, resulting in higher intracellular concentrations of small molecules. We sought to characterize PTs-CDs’ possible mechanisms of action after discovering that they can selectively kill cancer cells. Given that PTs have excellent antioxidant activity, particularly OA and GA. And one of the treatments for cancer is to induce intracellular ROS to produce cytotoxicity [24,25]. Moreover, PTs-CDs are sensitive to oxidants (
                           Figure S6
                        ) and produce elevated intracellular oxidant levels of ROS in cancer cells relative to non-cancerous cells [26,27]. We hypothesized that oxidative stress-derived ROS-mediated PTs-CDs exert anti-tumor properties.

According to serum biochemical and histopathological tests, PTs-CDs demonstrated extremely little in vivo toxicity (

                           Figure S12
                        ). Blood urea nitrogen (BUN), aspartate aminotransferase (AST) levels (as hepatotoxicity indicators, 
                           Figure S12
                        ), creatinine (CREA), serum alanine and aminotransferase (ALT) (as nephrotoxicity indicators, 
                           Figure S12
                        ) levels showed no significant changes after nude mice were injected with PTs-CDs (50 μL,1mg·kg−1). Meanwhile, no substantial tissue inflammation, cell necrosis, or apoptosis were found in the primary organs of the PTs-CDs-treated animals (lung, heart, spleen, kidney, and liver) (
                           Figure S13

                        ). Furthermore, at therapeutic dosages, PTs-CDs elicited no systemic immune response, with serum cytokines such as interleukin -1β (IL-1β), interleukin 6 (IL-6), and tumor necrosis factor-α (TNF-α) being equivalent to those of saline-treated animals (
                           Figure S14
                        ). In conclusion, PTs-CDs are safe for anti-tumor applications in vivo, with negligible non-specific toxicity to major organs and tissues.
